{"title_page": "Dead & Company", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Dead & Company\n| background      = group_or_band\n| image           = File:Dead & Company logo.png\n| image_size      = 150px\n| alt             = A red and blue circle with a white lightning bolt\n| caption         = Dead & Company logo\n| genre           = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| years_active    = 2015\u2013present\n| label           = \n| associated_acts = {{flatlist| \n* [[Grateful Dead]]\n* [[The Other Ones]]\n* [[The Dead (band)|The Dead]]\n* [[Go Ahead (band)|Go Ahead]]\n* [[RatDog]]\n* [[Rhythm Devils]]\n* [[BK3]]\n* [[Furthur (band)|Furthur]]\n}}\n| website         = {{URL|deadandcompany.com}}\n| current_members = \n* [[Mickey Hart]]\n* [[Bill Kreutzmann]]\n* [[John Mayer]]\n* [[Bob Weir]]\n* [[Oteil Burbridge]]\n* [[Jeff Chimenti]]\n| past_members    = \n}}\n[[File:Dead & Company 1 Nov 2015, New York, New York.jpg |thumb|Dead & Company at Madison Square Garden on November 1, 2015]]\n[[File:Dead-and-Company-Folsom-Field-2017.jpg|thumb|Dead & Company at Folsom Field on June 9, 2017]]\n'''Dead & Company''' is a band consisting of former [[Grateful Dead]] members [[Bob Weir]] (guitar), [[Mickey Hart]] (drums), and [[Bill Kreutzmann]] (drums), along with [[John Mayer]] (guitar), [[Oteil Burbridge]] (bass/drums), and [[Jeff Chimenti]] (keyboards).<ref name=DeadCo-FB >{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/pg/DeadandCompany/about/ |title=Dead & Company (Official Facebook Page) | work= | date= | accessdate=April 17, 2017 | last= | first= |quote= Dead & Company is: Mickey Hart - Drums / Percussion; Bill Kreutzmann - Drums / Percussion; John Mayer - Guitar / Vocals; Bob Weir - Guitar / Vocal; Oteil Burbridge - Bass; Jeff Chimenti - Keys}}</ref><ref name=CBS-rise>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/the-dead-rise-again-dead-company-on-tour/ |title=The Dead rise again: Dead & Company on tour | work=[[CBS News]] | date=June 2, 2016 | accessdate=April 16, 2017 | last= | first= | quote=The group includes three of the Grateful Dead's surviving core four: Mickey Hart, Bill Kreutzmann and Bob Weir, joined by John Mayer ('I'm going in tonight, like a 1930s boxer,' he exclaimed); former Allman Brothers bassist Oteil Burbidge; and keyboardist Jeff Chimenti.}}</ref><ref name=RS-Fricke >{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/bob-weir-on-dead-companys-future-john-mayers-classicist-style-20160531 |title=Bob Weir on Dead & Company's Future, John Mayer's 'Classicist' Style | work=[[Rolling Stone]] | date=May 31, 2016 | accessdate=April 16, 2017 | last=Fricke | first=David }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nMayer recounts that in 2011 he was listening to [[Pandora Radio|Pandora]] and happened upon the song \"[[Go to Heaven#Track listing|Althea]]\" by the [[Grateful Dead]], and that soon Grateful Dead music was all he would listen to.<ref name=deadtour>{{Cite web|title = John Mayer Talks Grateful Dead Legacy, Fare Thee Well and Learning to Play 'A Universe of Great Songs'|url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grateful-dead/6655956/john-mayer-grateful-dead-and-company-interview|website = Billboard|accessdate = November 18, 2015}}</ref>  In February 2015, while Mayer was guest hosting ''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]'', he invited Grateful Dead guitar player [[Bob Weir]] to join him in a studio performance.  A bond developed between the two, and while Weir and the other three surviving core members of the Grateful Dead were preparing for their 50th anniversary shows, dubbed [[Fare Thee Well: Celebrating 50 Years of the Grateful Dead|Fare Thee Well]], Mayer began practicing the band's large catalog of songs.  That August, Mayer and original Grateful Dead members Weir, Hart, and Kreutzmann formed the band, along with keyboardist Jeff Chimenti and bassist Oteil Burbridge. Mayer expressed a particularly strong enthusiasm toward playing with the new band.<ref name=RS-Kreps/><ref name=\"Stosuy 2015\"/>\n\n[[Phil Lesh]], the original bassist for the Grateful Dead, declined to join.<ref name=\"Lawrence\"/><ref name=\"Jambase\"/> [[Mike Gordon]] of [[Phish]] briefly auditioned for the bassist role but had to withdraw due to being too busy with other matters.<ref name=RS-Kreps>{{cite news|title=Grateful Dead Members, John Mayer Form Dead & Company|author=Kreps, Daniel|date=August 5, 2015|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/grateful-dead-members-john-mayer-form-dead-company-20150805|accessdate=August 5, 2015|website=Rolling Stone}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nDead & Company initially announced only one concert date on October 31, 2015, at [[Madison Square Garden]] in [[New York City|New York]] but announced a [[Dead & Company 2015 Tour|full tour]] shortly afterwards.<ref name=resurrect>{{cite web|title=The Grateful Dead Is Resurrected Once More, This Time with John Mayer|author=Halperin, Shirley|date=August 5, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grateful-dead/6655898/grateful-dead-john-mayer-show-tour|website=Billboard|accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref>  The shows were called \"magical\" (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'') and the tour was very well received.<ref name= NYT-Launch16>{{Citation |last= |first= |date=February 8, 2016 |title=Dead & Company To Launch 2016 Tour |publisher=[[New York Times]] |url=http://markets.on.nytimes.com/research/stocks/news/press_release.asp?docTag=201602080700PR_NEWS_USPRX____LA17152&feedID=600&press_symbol=3744685 |accessdate=April 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the band's final 2015 performance on December 31, 2015, Mayer told fans that they could expect more Dead & Company concerts in 2016 and this was confirmed by Weir when he was interviewed on [[Periscope (app)|Periscope]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jambands.com/news/2016/01/15/bob-weir-promises-more-dead-company-and-ratdog|title=Bob Weir Promises More Dead & Company and Ratdog|publisher=|accessdate=February 10, 2016}}</ref> The band initially had one performance confirmed for 2016 at the [[Bonnaroo Music Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/62590-bonnaroo-2016-lineup-announced/|title=Bonnaroo 2016 Lineup Announced|work=Pitchfork|accessdate=February 10, 2016}}</ref> but announced a full [[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2016|summer tour]] on February 8, 2016.<ref name= NYT-Launch16/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/dead-company-announce-summer-tour-20160208|title=Dead & Company Announce Summer Tour|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=February 10, 2016}}</ref> On February 18, 2016, the band performed on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jimmy Fallon]]'' to promote the tour.<ref>[http://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-to-perform-on-the-tonight-show-starring-jimmy-fallon [Updated&#93; Dead & Company To Perform On \u2018The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon\u2019<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===2016===\nIn 2016, Mayer and Weir expressed strong optimism about the band's future, including the possibility of new studio recordings.  Mayer said he \"will never close the door on Dead & Company, ever.\"<ref name=\"never-close\">{{Cite web|title = John Mayer Says He'll 'Never Close the Door on Dead & Company, Ever' |url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7326306/john-mayer-grateful-dead-company-interview |website = Billboard|accessdate = May 18, 2016}}</ref>  Weir spoke of a \"cosmic, out-of-body vision\" he had, and a subsequent dream, of the band continuing for decades hence:\n\n{{Quote|text=\"We were playing...and suddenly I was viewing this from about 20 feet behind my head, and I looked over at John from that point of view and it was 20 years later and John was almost fully gray. I looked over at Oteil and his hair was white. I looked over to my left and Jeff's hair was all gray.\" [''Then, looking to where he, Hart and Kreutzmann would be playing,]''&nbsp; \"it was new guys, younger guys holding forth, doing a great job...playing with fire and aplomb....It changed my whole view of what it is that we're up to. I find myself wondering, 'Well, what are they gonna be saying about this new approach or this honoring of this tradition? What are they gonna be saying about that in 200 or 300 years at the [[Berklee College of Music|Berklee School of Music]]?' That's the kind of stuff that goes through my head now because this legacy here, there's a chance now that they'll be talking about us in years to come. So I find it incumbent on myself to think in those terms.\" |author=Bob Weir |source=''Billboard''<ref name=\"never-close\"/> }}\n\nWhen Dead & Company played their first festival performance at the 2016 [[Bonnaroo Music Festival]], former Grateful Dead vocalist [[Donna Jean Godchaux]] sat in with the band for several songs. She joined the band again for their shows at [[Citi Field]] in [[Flushing, Queens|Flushing, NY]] on June 25 and 26, 2016, and at [[Fenway Park]] in [[Boston|Boston, MA]] on July 15 and 16, 2016.\n\n===2017===\nOn December 1, 2016, Dead & Company officially announced their [[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2017|2017 Summer Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-announces-summer-tour-2017 |title=Dead & Company Announce Summer Tour 2017 |publisher=JamBase |date=December 1, 2016 |accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref> The tour began on May 27, 2017 and wrapped up on July 1, 2017. The tour consisted of 20 shows in 15 cities.\n\nIn a 2017 interview with ''Rolling Stone'', Phil Lesh praised the band's performances, saying \"I think they're doing a great job.  They're bringing the music to the people just like we always wanted to do, and I commend them for it. I hope they're having a good time. It's not something I could do myself. I'm done with that kind of touring.\"<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/phil-lesh-on-grateful-dead-doc-long-strange-trip-its-not-the-whole-story-110241/ | title=Phil Lesh on Grateful Dead Doc \u2018Long Strange Trip\u2019: \u2018It\u2019s Not the Whole Story\u2019 | first=Kory | last=Grow | date=May 25, 2017 | work=Rolling Stone | accessdate=February 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn September 7, 2017, Dead & Company officially announced their [[Dead & Company Fall Tour 2017|Fall Tour 2017]].<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dead-company-detail-fall-tour-205724/ | title=Dead & Company Detail Fall Tour | first=Jon | last=Blistein | date=September 7, 2017 | work=Rolling Stone | accessdate=February 22, 2019}}</ref> The tour began on November 12, 2017 and was scheduled to wrap up on December 8, 2017. However, on December 5, Mayer was hospitalized for an emergency appendectomy, which postponed the New Orleans show that night. Dead & Company subsequently postponed the remaining tour dates, rescheduling them in February, following several independent shows in Mexico. The Fall Tour consisted of 16 shows in 14 cities.\n\n===2018===\nOn May 30, 2018, the band began their [[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2018|2018 summer tour]], originally set to end on July 14<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/dead-and-company-tour-2018/|title=Dead and Company Begin Summer Tour: Set List and Video|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|language=en|access-date=June 1, 2018}}</ref> but extended to include two shows at the [[Lockn' Festival]] on August 25 and 26.<ref>[http://www.locknfestival.com/lineup/schedule 2018 Lock'n lineup]</ref><ref name=\"Official-1\">{{cite web | url=http://deadandcompany.com/ | title=Dead & Company | publisher=Dead & Company | accessdate=July 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nFrom May 31 to July 6, the band played their [[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2019|2019 Summer Tour]].  They performed 19 concerts at 14 locations across the U.S.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bernstein |first1=Scott |date=November 29, 2018 |title=Dead & Company Announces Summer Tour 2019 |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-summer-tour-2019 |website=Jam Base |access-date=June 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Dave |last=Brooks |date=November 29, 2018 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/live/8487142/dead-company-2019-summer-tour-dates-cities |title=Dead and Company 2019 Summer Tour: See the Dates and Cities |website=Billboard |access-date=July 8, 2019}}</ref> The band played a short fall tour in New York City on October 31 and November 1 followed by 2 shows at Uniondale's Nassau Coliseum on November 5 and 6. They then moved south to Hampton, Virginia on November 8 and 9.<ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=Bernstein |date=August 15, 2019 |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-fall-tour-2019 |title=Dead & Company Announce Brief Fall Tour 2019 |website=JamBase |access-date=August 15, 2019}}</ref> On December 27 and 28, they played at The Forum in Inglewood (Los Angeles), California as part of their \"Fun Run\" tour. On December 30 and 31, they played in their hometown of San Francisco at the Chase Center, featuring a bi-plane that descended from the ceiling of the Chase Center carrying the daughters of Jerry Garcia, Trixie Garcia and her half-sister, Ken Kesey\u2019s daughter Sunshine Kesey, dropping rose petals on the audience as they toured the arena.<ref>https://deadandcompany.com/</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jeff |last=Weiss |date=January 2, 2020 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8547221/dead-company-new-years-eve-live-review |title=The Long Strange Trip of Dead & Company Continues with Legacy-Honoring, Career-Spanning New Year's Eve Show |website=Billboard |access-date=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\nIn January 2020, Dead & Company played three concerts as part of the \"Playing in the Sand\" event at the Moon Palace resort in [[Canc\u00fan|Canc\u00fan, Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=Bernstein |date=July 8, 2019 |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-playing-in-the-sand-2020 |title=Dead & Company Detail Playing in the Sand 2020 |website=JamBase |access-date=July 10, 2019}}</ref> The band will also perform at [[New Orleans Jazz & Heritage Festival|New Orleans Jazz Fest]].<ref>https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-who-stevie-nicks-dead-and-company-jazz-fest-2020-938819/</ref> The band will also embark on a [[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2020|2020 Summer Tour]], consisting of 17 dates at 14 locations from July 10 to August 8.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dead & Company Details Summer Tour 2020|url=https://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-summer-tour-2020|first=David|last=Bernstein|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020|website=JamBase.com|publisher=JamBase, Inc.}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\nThe band has released no studio recordings, but all of the concerts from their 2016, 2017, 2018 and 2019 tours have been (or are being) released on CD, on iTunes, on streaming services and through their Livedead.co website.\n\n==Members==\n*[[Bob Weir]] \u2013 rhythm guitar, vocals\n*[[Bill Kreutzmann]] \u2013 drums\n*[[Mickey Hart]] \u2013 percussion, drums\n*[[John Mayer]] \u2013 lead guitar, vocals\n*[[Oteil Burbridge]] \u2013 bass guitar, percussion, vocals\n*[[Jeff Chimenti]] \u2013 keyboards, backing vocals\n\n==Tours==\n*[[Dead & Company 2015 Tour]]\n*[[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2016]]\n*[[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2017]]\n*[[Dead & Company Fall Tour 2017]]\n*[[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2018]]\n*[[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2019]]\n*Dead & Company Fall Fun Run 2019\n*[[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2020]]\n\n===Standalone shows===\nThe band has played thirteen concerts that are not officially part of any tour:\n*May 23, 2016, [[The Fillmore]], San Francisco (free show)<ref name=0523-CBS>{{cite web | url=http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2016/05/18/dead-company-announce-free-pay-it-forward-show-at-fillmore/= | title=Dead & Company Invite Fans To Free Fillmore Show | work=CBS SF Bay Area | date=May 18, 2016 | accessdate=March 5, 2017 | last= | first= }}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*November 9, 2017, [[AT&T Park]], San Francisco (single set at ''Band Together Bay Area'' benefit concert for victims of the [[2017 California wildfires]])<ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=Bernstein |date=November 10, 2017 |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-metallica-band-together-northern-california-fire-victims |title=Dead & Company, Metallica & More Band Together For Northern California Fire Victims  |website=JamBase |access-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n*February 15, 17 and 18, 2018, ''Playing In The Sand'', Barcel\u00f3 Maya resort in [[Riviera Maya]], Mexico<ref name=playin>{{cite web | url=https://deadandcompany.com/events/435873 | title=Playing In The Sand | publisher=Dead & Company | accessdate=January 24, 2018}}</ref>\n*January 17, 18, 19 and 20, 2019, ''Playing In The Sand'', Barcel\u00f3 Maya resort in [[Riviera Maya]], Mexico<ref name=playin2>{{cite web | url=https://playinginthesand.com/ | title=Playing In The Sand | publisher=Dead & Company | accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref>\n*January 16, 17, 18 and 19, 2020, ''Playing In The Sand'', Moon Palace Canc\u00fan resort in [[Riviera Maya]], Mexico<ref>https://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-playing-in-the-sand-2020</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fare Thee Well: Celebrating 50 Years of the Grateful Dead]]\n* [[Reunions of the Grateful Dead]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"Stosuy 2015\">{{cite web | last=Stosuy | first=Brandon | title=Grateful Dead Members to Tour as Dead & Company With John Mayer | website=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] | date=August 5, 2015 | url=http://pitchfork.com/news/60684-grateful-dead-members-to-tour-as-dead-company-with-john-mayer/ | accessdate=August 8, 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Lawrence\">{{cite web | last=Lawrence | first=Jesse | title=Could Dead & Company Ticket Prices At MSG Reach Levels Of Fare Thee Well Shows? | website=[[Forbes]] | date=August 5, 2015 | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jesselawrence/2015/08/05/could-dead-company-tickets-at-madison-square-garden-reach-fare-thee-well-prices/ | accessdate=August 8, 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Jambase\">{{cite web | url=http://www.jambase.com/Articles/124365/Phil-Lesh-and-Friends-Fall-Shows-At-Capitol-Theatre | title=Phil Lesh & Friends Fall Shows at Capitol Theatre | publisher=[[JamBase]] | date=March 17, 2015 | accessdate=August 7, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web | title=New life for Dead & Company | website=[[USA Today]] | date=August 5, 2015 | author=Mansfield, Brian | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2015/08/05/dead-and-company-grateful-dead-john-mayer/31168487/ | accessdate=August 8, 2015}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://deadandcompany.com}}\n\n{{Grateful Dead}}\n{{Bob Weir}}\n{{Bill Kreutzmann}}\n{{Mickey Hart}}\n{{John Mayer}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dead and Company}}\n[[Category:American rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Jam bands]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2015]]\n[[Category:John Mayer]]\n[[Category:Grateful Dead]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Dead & Company\n| background      = group_or_band\n| image           = File:Dead & Company logo.png\n| image_size      = 150px\n| alt             = A red and blue circle with a white lightning bolt\n| caption         = Dead & Company logo\n| genre           = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| years_active    = 2015\u2013present\n| label           = \n| associated_acts = {{flatlist| \n* [[Grateful Dead]]\n* [[The Other Ones]]\n* [[The Dead (band)|The Dead]]\n* [[Go Ahead (band)|Go Ahead]]\n* [[RatDog]]\n* [[Rhythm Devils]]\n* [[BK3]]\n* [[Furthur (band)|Furthur]]\n}}\n| website         = {{URL|deadandcompany.com}}\n| current_members = \n* [[Mickey Hart]]\n* [[Bill Kreutzmann]]\n* [[John Mayer]]\n* [[Bob Weir]]\n* [[Oteil Burbridge]]\n* [[Jeff Chimenti]]\n| past_members    = \n}}\n[[File:Dead & Company 1 Nov 2015, New York, New York.jpg |thumb|Dead & Company at Madison Square Garden on November 1, 2015]]\n[[File:Dead-and-Company-Folsom-Field-2017.jpg|thumb|Dead & Company at Folsom Field on June 9, 2017]]\n'''Dead & Company''' is a band consisting of former [[Grateful Dead]] members [[Bob Weir]] (guitar), [[Mickey Hart]] (drums), and [[Bill Kreutzmann]] (drums), along with [[John Mayer]] (guitar), [[Oteil Burbridge]] (bass/drums), and [[Jeff Chimenti]] (keyboards).<ref name=DeadCo-FB >{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/pg/DeadandCompany/about/ |title=Dead & Company (Official Facebook Page) | work= | date= | accessdate=2017-04-17 | last= | first= |quote= Dead & Company is: Mickey Hart - Drums / Percussion; Bill Kreutzmann - Drums / Percussion; John Mayer - Guitar / Vocals; Bob Weir - Guitar / Vocal; Oteil Burbridge - Bass; Jeff Chimenti - Keys}}</ref><ref name=CBS-rise>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/the-dead-rise-again-dead-company-on-tour/ |title=The Dead rise again: Dead & Company on tour | work=[[CBS News]] | date=2016-06-02 | accessdate=2017-04-16 | last= | first= | quote=The group includes three of the Grateful Dead's surviving core four: Mickey Hart, Bill Kreutzmann and Bob Weir, joined by John Mayer ('I'm going in tonight, like a 1930s boxer,' he exclaimed); former Allman Brothers bassist Oteil Burbidge; and keyboardist Jeff Chimenti.}}</ref><ref name=RS-Fricke >{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/bob-weir-on-dead-companys-future-john-mayers-classicist-style-20160531 |title=Bob Weir on Dead & Company's Future, John Mayer's 'Classicist' Style | work=[[Rolling Stone]] | date=2016-05-31 | accessdate=2017-04-16 | last=Fricke | first=David }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nMayer recounts that in 2011 he was listening to [[Pandora Radio|Pandora]] and happened upon the song \"[[Go to Heaven#Track listing|Althea]]\" by the [[Grateful Dead]], and that soon Grateful Dead music was all he would listen to.<ref name=deadtour>{{Cite web|title = John Mayer Talks Grateful Dead Legacy, Fare Thee Well and Learning to Play 'A Universe of Great Songs'|url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grateful-dead/6655956/john-mayer-grateful-dead-and-company-interview|website = Billboard|accessdate = 2015-11-18}}</ref>  In February 2015, while Mayer was guest hosting ''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]'', he invited Grateful Dead guitar player [[Bob Weir]] to join him in a studio performance.  A bond developed between the two, and while Weir and the other three surviving core members of the Grateful Dead were preparing for their 50th anniversary shows, dubbed [[Fare Thee Well: Celebrating 50 Years of the Grateful Dead|Fare Thee Well]], Mayer began practicing the band's large catalog of songs.  That August, Mayer and original Grateful Dead members Weir, Hart, and Kreutzmann formed the band, along with keyboardist Jeff Chimenti and bassist Oteil Burbridge. Mayer expressed a particularly strong enthusiasm toward playing with the new band.<ref name=RS-Kreps/><ref name=\"Stosuy 2015\"/>\n\n[[Phil Lesh]], the original bassist for the Grateful Dead, declined to join.<ref name=\"Lawrence\"/><ref name=\"Jambase\"/> [[Mike Gordon]] of [[Phish]] briefly auditioned for the bassist role but had to withdraw due to being too busy with other matters.<ref name=RS-Kreps>{{cite news|title=Grateful Dead Members, John Mayer Form Dead & Company|author=Kreps, Daniel|date=August 5, 2015|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/grateful-dead-members-john-mayer-form-dead-company-20150805|accessdate=August 5, 2015|website=Rolling Stone}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nDead & Company initially announced only one concert date on October 31, 2015, at [[Madison Square Garden]] in [[New York City|New York]] but announced a [[Dead & Company 2015 Tour|full tour]] shortly afterwards.<ref name=resurrect>{{cite web|title=The Grateful Dead Is Resurrected Once More, This Time with John Mayer|author=Halperin, Shirley|date=August 5, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grateful-dead/6655898/grateful-dead-john-mayer-show-tour|website=Billboard|accessdate=August 5, 2015}}</ref>  The shows were called \"magical\" (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'') and the tour was very well received.<ref name= NYT-Launch16>{{Citation |last= |first= |date=February 8, 2016 |title=Dead & Company To Launch 2016 Tour |publisher=[[New York Times]] |url=http://markets.on.nytimes.com/research/stocks/news/press_release.asp?docTag=201602080700PR_NEWS_USPRX____LA17152&feedID=600&press_symbol=3744685 |accessdate=April 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the band's final 2015 performance on December 31, 2015, Mayer told fans that they could expect more Dead & Company concerts in 2016 and this was confirmed by Weir when he was interviewed on [[Periscope (app)|Periscope]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jambands.com/news/2016/01/15/bob-weir-promises-more-dead-company-and-ratdog|title=Bob Weir Promises More Dead & Company and Ratdog|publisher=|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref> The band initially had one performance confirmed for 2016 at the [[Bonnaroo Music Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/62590-bonnaroo-2016-lineup-announced/|title=Bonnaroo 2016 Lineup Announced|work=Pitchfork|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref> but announced a full [[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2016|summer tour]] on February 8, 2016.<ref name= NYT-Launch16/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/dead-company-announce-summer-tour-20160208|title=Dead & Company Announce Summer Tour|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref> On February 18, 2016, the band performed on ''[[The Tonight Show with Jimmy Fallon]]'' to promote the tour.<ref>[http://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-to-perform-on-the-tonight-show-starring-jimmy-fallon [Updated&#93; Dead & Company To Perform On \u2018The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon\u2019<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===2016===\nIn 2016, Mayer and Weir expressed strong optimism about the band's future, including the possibility of new studio recordings.  Mayer said he \"will never close the door on Dead & Company, ever.\"<ref name=\"never-close\">{{Cite web|title = John Mayer Says He'll 'Never Close the Door on Dead & Company, Ever' |url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7326306/john-mayer-grateful-dead-company-interview |website = Billboard|accessdate = 2016-05-18}}</ref>  Weir spoke of a \"cosmic, out-of-body vision\" he had, and a subsequent dream, of the band continuing for decades hence:\n\n{{Quote|text=\"We were playing...and suddenly I was viewing this from about 20 feet behind my head, and I looked over at John from that point of view and it was 20 years later and John was almost fully gray. I looked over at Oteil and his hair was white. I looked over to my left and Jeff's hair was all gray.\" [''Then, looking to where he, Hart and Kreutzmann would be playing,]''&nbsp; \"it was new guys, younger guys holding forth, doing a great job...playing with fire and aplomb....It changed my whole view of what it is that we're up to. I find myself wondering, 'Well, what are they gonna be saying about this new approach or this honoring of this tradition? What are they gonna be saying about that in 200 or 300 years at the [[Berklee College of Music|Berklee School of Music]]?' That's the kind of stuff that goes through my head now because this legacy here, there's a chance now that they'll be talking about us in years to come. So I find it incumbent on myself to think in those terms.\" |author=Bob Weir |source=''Billboard''<ref name=\"never-close\"/> }}\n\nWhen Dead & Company played their first festival performance at the 2016 [[Bonnaroo Music Festival]], former Grateful Dead vocalist [[Donna Jean Godchaux]] sat in with the band for several songs. She joined the band again for their shows at [[Citi Field]] in [[Flushing, Queens|Flushing, NY]] on June 25 and 26, 2016, and at [[Fenway Park]] in [[Boston|Boston, MA]] on July 15 and 16, 2016.\n\n===2017===\nOn December 1, 2016, Dead & Company officially announced their [[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2017|2017 Summer Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-announces-summer-tour-2017 |title=Dead & Company Announce Summer Tour 2017 |publisher=JamBase |date=December 1, 2016 |accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref> The tour began on May 27, 2017 and wrapped up on July 1, 2017. The tour consisted of 20 shows in 15 cities.\n\nIn a 2017 interview with ''Rolling Stone'', Phil Lesh praised the band's performances, saying \"I think they're doing a great job.  They're bringing the music to the people just like we always wanted to do, and I commend them for it. I hope they're having a good time. It's not something I could do myself. I'm done with that kind of touring.\"<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/phil-lesh-on-grateful-dead-doc-long-strange-trip-its-not-the-whole-story-110241/ | title=Phil Lesh on Grateful Dead Doc \u2018Long Strange Trip\u2019: \u2018It\u2019s Not the Whole Story\u2019 | first=Kory | last=Grow | date=May 25, 2017 | work=Rolling Stone | accessdate=February 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn September 7, 2017, Dead & Company officially announced their [[Dead & Company Fall Tour 2017|Fall Tour 2017]].<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dead-company-detail-fall-tour-205724/ | title=Dead & Company Detail Fall Tour | first=Jon | last=Blistein | date=September 7, 2017 | work=Rolling Stone | accessdate=February 22, 2019}}</ref> The tour began on November 12, 2017 and was scheduled to wrap up on December 8, 2017. However, on December 5, Mayer was hospitalized for an emergency appendectomy, which postponed the New Orleans show that night. Dead & Company subsequently postponed the remaining tour dates, rescheduling them in February, following several independent shows in Mexico. The Fall Tour consisted of 16 shows in 14 cities.\n\n===2018===\nOn May 30, 2018, the band began their [[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2018|2018 summer tour]], originally set to end on July 14<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/dead-and-company-tour-2018/|title=Dead and Company Begin Summer Tour: Set List and Video|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|language=en|access-date=2018-06-01}}</ref> but extended to include two shows at the [[Lockn' Festival]] on August 25 and 26.<ref>[http://www.locknfestival.com/lineup/schedule 2018 Lock'n lineup]</ref><ref name=\"Official-1\">{{cite web | url=http://deadandcompany.com/ | title=Dead & Company | publisher=Dead & Company | accessdate=July 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nFrom May 31 to July 6, the band played their [[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2019|2019 Summer Tour]].  They performed 19 concerts at 14 locations across the U.S.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bernstein |first1=Scott |date=November 29, 2018 |title=Dead & Company Announces Summer Tour 2019 |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-summer-tour-2019 |website=Jam Base |access-date=June 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Dave |last=Brooks |date=November 29, 2018 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/live/8487142/dead-company-2019-summer-tour-dates-cities |title=Dead and Company 2019 Summer Tour: See the Dates and Cities |website=Billboard |access-date=July 8, 2019}}</ref> The band played a short fall tour in New York City on October 31 and November 1 followed by 2 shows at Uniondale's Nassau Coliseum on November 5th and 6th. They then moved south to Hampton, Virginia on November 8 and 9.<ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=Bernstein |date=August 15, 2019 |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-fall-tour-2019 |title=Dead & Company Announce Brief Fall Tour 2019 |website=JamBase |access-date=August 15, 2019}}</ref> On December 27 and 28, they played at The Forum in Inglewood (Los Angeles), California as part of their \"Fun Run\" tour. On December 30 and 31, they played in their hometown of San Francisco at the Chase Center, featuring a bi-plane that descended from the ceiling of the Chase Center carrying the daughters of Jerry Garcia, Trixie Garcia and her half-sister, Ken Kesey\u2019s daughter Sunshine Kesey, dropping rose petals on the audience as they toured the arena.<ref>https://deadandcompany.com/</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jeff |last=Weiss |date=January 2, 2020 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8547221/dead-company-new-years-eve-live-review |title=The Long Strange Trip of Dead & Company Continues with Legacy-Honoring, Career-Spanning New Year's Eve Show |website=Billboard |access-date=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\nIn January 2020, Dead & Company played three concerts as part of the \"Playing in the Sand\" event at the Moon Palace resort in [[Canc\u00fan|Canc\u00fan, Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=Bernstein |date=July 8, 2019 |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-playing-in-the-sand-2020 |title=Dead & Company Detail Playing in the Sand 2020 |website=JamBase |access-date=July 10, 2019}}</ref> The band will also perform at [[New Orleans Jazz & Heritage Festival|New Orleans Jazz Fest]].<ref>https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/the-who-stevie-nicks-dead-and-company-jazz-fest-2020-938819/</ref> The band will also embark on a [[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2020|2020 Summer Tour]], consisting of 17 dates at 14 locations from July 10 to August 8.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dead & Company Details Summer Tour 2020|url=https://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-summer-tour-2020|first=David|last=Bernstein|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020|website=JamBase.com|publisher=JamBase, Inc.}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\nThe band has released no studio recordings, but all of the concerts from their 2016, 2017, 2018 and 2019 tours have been (or are being) released on CD, on iTunes, on streaming services and through their Livedead.co website.\n\n==Members==\n*[[Bob Weir]] \u2013 rhythm guitar, vocals\n*[[Bill Kreutzmann]] \u2013 drums\n*[[Mickey Hart]] \u2013 percussion, drums\n*[[John Mayer]] \u2013 lead guitar, vocals\n*[[Oteil Burbridge]] \u2013 bass guitar, percussion, vocals\n*[[Jeff Chimenti]] \u2013 keyboards, backing vocals\n\n==Tours==\n*[[Dead & Company 2015 Tour]]\n*[[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2016]]\n*[[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2017]]\n*[[Dead & Company Fall Tour 2017]]\n*[[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2018]]\n*[[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2019]]\n*Dead & Company Fall Fun Run 2019\n*[[Dead & Company Summer Tour 2020]]\n\n===Standalone shows===\nThe band has played thirteen concerts that are not officially part of any tour:\n*May 23, 2016, [[The Fillmore]], San Francisco (free show)<ref name=0523-CBS>{{cite web | url=http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2016/05/18/dead-company-announce-free-pay-it-forward-show-at-fillmore/= | title=Dead & Company Invite Fans To Free Fillmore Show | work=CBS SF Bay Area | date=2016-05-18 | accessdate=2017-03-05 | last= | first= }}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*November 9, 2017, [[AT&T Park]], San Francisco (single set at ''Band Together Bay Area'' benefit concert for victims of the [[2017 California wildfires]])<ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=Bernstein |date=November 10, 2017 |url=https://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-metallica-band-together-northern-california-fire-victims |title=Dead & Company, Metallica & More Band Together For Northern California Fire Victims  |website=JamBase |access-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n*February 15, 17 and 18, 2018, ''Playing In The Sand'', Barcel\u00f3 Maya resort in [[Riviera Maya]], Mexico<ref name=playin>{{cite web | url=https://deadandcompany.com/events/435873 | title=Playing In The Sand | publisher=Dead & Company | accessdate=January 24, 2018}}</ref>\n*January 17, 18, 19 and 20, 2019, ''Playing In The Sand'', Barcel\u00f3 Maya resort in [[Riviera Maya]], Mexico<ref name=playin2>{{cite web | url=https://playinginthesand.com/ | title=Playing In The Sand | publisher=Dead & Company | accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref>\n*January 16, 17, 18, and 19, 2020, ''Playing In The Sand'', Moon Palace Canc\u00fan resort in [[Riviera Maya]], Mexico<ref>https://www.jambase.com/article/dead-company-playing-in-the-sand-2020</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fare Thee Well: Celebrating 50 Years of the Grateful Dead]]\n* [[Reunions of the Grateful Dead]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"Stosuy 2015\">{{cite web | last=Stosuy | first=Brandon | title=Grateful Dead Members to Tour as Dead & Company With John Mayer | website=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] | date=August 5, 2015 | url=http://pitchfork.com/news/60684-grateful-dead-members-to-tour-as-dead-company-with-john-mayer/ | accessdate=August 8, 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Lawrence\">{{cite web | last=Lawrence | first=Jesse | title=Could Dead & Company Ticket Prices At MSG Reach Levels Of Fare Thee Well Shows? | website=[[Forbes]] | date=August 5, 2015 | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jesselawrence/2015/08/05/could-dead-company-tickets-at-madison-square-garden-reach-fare-thee-well-prices/ | accessdate=August 8, 2015}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Jambase\">{{cite web | url=http://www.jambase.com/Articles/124365/Phil-Lesh-and-Friends-Fall-Shows-At-Capitol-Theatre | title=Phil Lesh & Friends Fall Shows at Capitol Theatre | publisher=[[JamBase]] | date=March 17, 2015 | accessdate=7 August 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web | title=New life for Dead & Company | website=[[USA Today]] | date=August 5, 2015 | author=Mansfield, Brian | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2015/08/05/dead-and-company-grateful-dead-john-mayer/31168487/ | accessdate=August 8, 2015}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://deadandcompany.com}}\n\n{{Grateful Dead}}\n{{Bob Weir}}\n{{Bill Kreutzmann}}\n{{Mickey Hart}}\n{{John Mayer}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dead and Company}}\n[[Category:American rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Jam bands]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in the Uni